      "message": "for less than ~50- ints, it\u0027s hard to beat external log-based routine that doesn\u0027t do small slice optimization.\n\nAnd it turns out Go doesn\u0027t, which kinda makes sense: if predicate is expensive, you want minimal possible number of predicate() calls.\n\nFrom my C++ perf optimizing hat:\n\n  const LOG_IF_LONGER_THAN \u003d 8\n  l, r :\u003d 0, len(ns)\n  for l+LOG_IF_LONGER_THAN \u003c r {\n    switch m :\u003d int(uint(l+r) \u003e\u003e 1); {\n    case ns[m] \u003d\u003d idx:\n      return true\n    case ns[m] \u003c idx:\n      l \u003d m + 1\n    default:\n      r \u003d m\n    }\n  }\n  for l \u003c r {\n    if ns[l] \u003d\u003d idx {\n      return true\n    }\n    l++\n  }\n  return false\n\n\nI\u0027d bet it works much better than inlined Go search. I miss proper templates and real perf 😞",
